# Database Patterns

## Data model — how things are linked

| Concept | Table | Key columns |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| Product ↔ Supplier assignment | `reorder_rules` | `product_id`, `primary_supplier_id` |
| Active assignment | `reorder_rules` | `is_active = true` |
| Remove assignment | `reorder_rules` | set `is_active = false` |

Products and suppliers are **never directly linked**. The join is always through `reorder_rules`.

## Never upsert with onConflict unless the constraint is verified in prod

The remote Supabase instance may not have all migrations applied.
`upsert(..., { onConflict: "shop_id,product_id" })` throws a Postgres error
if the unique constraint doesn't exist. Always use check-then-insert/update:

```ts
// ✅ CORRECT — works regardless of whether the unique constraint exists
const { data: existing } = await supabase
  .from("reorder_rules")
  .select("id")
  .eq("shop_id", shopId)
  .eq("product_id", productId)
  .maybeSingle();

if (existing?.id) {
  await supabase.from("reorder_rules").update(payload).eq("id", existing.id);
} else {
  await supabase.from("reorder_rules").insert(payload);
}

// ❌ WRONG — crashes when unique constraint is missing in prod
await supabase.from("reorder_rules").upsert(payload, { onConflict: "shop_id,product_id" });
```

## Always return { error } from mutation functions

```ts
// ✅ CORRECT
export async function deactivateReorderRule(...) {
  const { error } = await supabase.from(...).update(...);
  if (error) return { error: error.message };
  return { error: null };
}

// ❌ WRONG — caller can't tell if the operation failed
export async function deactivateReorderRule(...) {
  await supabase.from(...).update(...); // fire-and-forget
}
```

## Hard delete — nullify FKs first

Before deleting a supplier (or any record referenced by FKs):
1. Null out `reorder_rules.primary_supplier_id`
2. Null out `reorder_rules.backup_supplier_id`
3. Null out `purchase_orders.supplier_id`
4. Then delete the supplier row

This preserves historical PO data while allowing the delete to succeed.

## Shopify product sync — query cost limit is 1000

`products(first: 250, variants(first: 100, inventoryLevels(first: 5)))` costs ~1047.
Stay under 1000:

```graphql
# ✅ CORRECT
products(first: 50) {          # paginate more pages instead
  variants(first: 10) {
    inventoryItem {
      inventoryLevels(first: 3) {
        quantities(names: ["available"]) { name quantity }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

`InventoryLevel.available` was removed in API version 2025-10. Use `quantities(names: ["available"])`.
